<h5><a name="nat" id="nat">NAT</a></h5>
<div class="level5">

<p>
If you can connect to other servers, but other cannot connect to you, chances are you&#039;re behind NAT.
</p>

<p>
If the machine performing NAT is a Linux machine, you could use:
</p>
<pre class="code">iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p udp -d 195.169.216.157 --dport 9898 -j DNAT --to 172.16.3.2:9898</pre>

<p>
(where &#039;195.169.216.157&#039; is your public IP, and &#039;172.16.3.2&#039; the local IP of your machine)
</p>

</div>

<h5><a name="port_forwarding" id="port_forwarding">Port Forwarding</a></h5>
<div class="level5">

<p>
Another common problem is that you are simply behind a router or firewall. The most common solution is to open your ports, or port forwarding. For more information on port forwarding and router-specific instructions, visit <a href="http://www.portforward.com/" class="urlextern" title="http://www.portforward.com/"  rel="nofollow">http://www.portforward.com/</a>
</p>

</div>
</div>
